:INFO
How to Read a Bad Shot
Every off shot leaves a clue. Sour, bitter, watery, and astringent each \
point to a different variable. Learn to identify the taste before \
reaching for the grinder.

:INFO
Shot Tastes Sour
Under extraction. Water passed through the puck too quickly. The fix is a \
finer grind, a higher dose, or a longer yield. Check that your water \
temperature is at least 90 Celsius.

:INFO
Shot Tastes Bitter
Over extraction. Water spent too long in contact with the grounds. Make \
the grind coarser first. If that does not help, lower the dose slightly \
or shorten the yield.

:INFO
Shot Is Watery and Weak
The grind is likely too coarse or the dose too low. Weigh your dose. A \
scale removes this variable entirely. If the dose is correct, tighten the \
grind one step.

:INFO
Shot Runs Too Fast (under 20 seconds)
Channeling or a grind that is too coarse. Check your distribution and \
tamp before touching the grinder. A fast shot with good flavor is rare \
but possible with a light roast at a wide grind.

:INFO
Shot Runs Too Slow (over 35 seconds)
The grind is too fine or the dose is too high. Loosen the grind one step. \
If the machine is struggling to push water through, the puck may also be \
saturating unevenly.

:COUNTER.half
20 to 30 Second Target
|
:COUNTER.half
88 to 94 Celsius Range

:NOTE
When Nothing Works
If shots are inconsistent despite correct technique, check your grinder \
burrs. Worn burrs produce uneven particle sizes that make any recipe \
unstable. Burr replacement is the highest impact maintenance step on any \
grinder used daily for more than a year.

